# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bob-barker
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] A **special election for Florida's 13th congressional district** was held March 11, 2014, to elect a member of the United States House of Representatives, following the death of incumbent Republican Congressman Bill Young on October 18, 2013.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] Primary elections were held on January 14, 2014.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] Young, who had already announced that he would not be running for re-election in 2014, was re-elected in 2012 with 57 percent of the vote.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] With 100% of the precincts reporting, David Jolly was declared the winner.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] On October 9, 2013, Republican Bill Young, who had held this Tampa Bay-area district since 1971, announced that he would not run for re-election to a twenty-second term in 2014.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] He died nine days later and this special election was called to fill his seat.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] Though Young had been re-elected by wide margins, the district in recent years had become competitive.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] In the four most recent presidential elections, it was won by Al Gore over George W.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] Bush in 2000 51%-49%, by Bush with 51%-49% in 2004, by Barack Obama over John McCain 51%-47% and again carried by Obama in 2012 by a narrower 50%-49% over Mitt Romney.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] Given this, some political commentators and journalists viewed this election as a bellwether for the fall 2014 elections.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] While discounting the idea of special elections as bellwethers, political scientists agreed the result was a data point that public sentiment favored Republicans.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] One voter was confused by a website called "sinkforcongress2014" accepting donations to the National Republican Congressional Committee to defeat Sink and other Democrats, thinking it was a pro-Sink website.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] His $250 donation was refunded by the NRCC.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] David Jolly, Lucas Overby, and Alex Sink, the three candidates appearing on the ballot for the special election, took part in a televised debate on February 3, 2014.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] Petersburg College and co-hosted by the Tampa Bay Times and Bay News 9, the event aired live on C-SPAN 3.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] Al Ruechel, Adam Smith, and Amy Hollyfield served as moderators.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] The debate can be viewed in its entirety here.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] A non-scientific poll conducted after the debate by Bay News 9 indicated that overall viewers felt David Jolly had won with 37% of the vote, followed by Alex Sink with 33% and Lucas Overby with 30%.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] During the campaign, OpenSecrets reported on February 13, 2014, that outside groups had spent $3.5 million on the election, with $2.6 million of that from groups that support Jolly.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] This makes it the most expensive election of the 2014 cycle so far and one of the most expensive special congressional elections in history.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] The Associated Press reported that $11 million total was spent as the Democratic Party poured money into the campaign in its final weeks.
[src:bob-barker/2014-florida-s-13th-congressional-district-special-election] In the end, Sink outspent Jolly by three to one on television ads, as well as outspending him overall.
[src:bob-barker/26th-daytime-emmy-awards] The **26th Daytime Emmy Awards** were held in 1999 to commemorate excellence in daytime television programming from the previous year (1998).
[src:bob-barker/26th-daytime-emmy-awards] The main ceremonies were held May 21, 1999, at The Theater in Madison Square Garden in New York City and were televised live by CBS.
[src:bob-barker/26th-daytime-emmy-awards] Memorable moments that occurred at the ceremonies included the ABC soap opera *General Hospital* winning a record number of Daytime Emmys with a total of eight, and Susan Lucci's first-ever win in the Outstanding Lead Actress category after losing a total of 18 times.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The story is framed by a voice-over narrative by the Spartan soldier Dilios (David Wenham).
[src:bob-barker/300-film] As an unreliable narrator, Dillos introduces various historical inaccuracies and other fantastical elements, placing *300* within the genre of historical fantasy.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] *300* was filmed mostly with a superimposition chroma key technique to replicate the imagery of the original comics.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] An unfinished cut of *300* premiered at the Austin Butt-Numb-A-Thon on December 9, 2006.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The completed film then premiered at the Berlin International Film Festival on February 14, 2007, before being released in both conventional and IMAX screens in the United States on March 9, and on home media on July 31.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The film received generally positive reviews from critics, who praised its visuals and style but received criticism from historians, who criticized its historical inaccuracies, most notably its depiction of the Persians, which some characterized as Persophobic.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Grossing over $468.8 million, the film's opening was the 24th-largest in box office history at the time, and became the tenth highest-grossing film of 2007.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The film earned a leading ten nominations at the 34th Saturn Awards, winning two for Best Action, Adventure, or Thriller Film and Best Director (for Snyder).
[src:bob-barker/300-film] A sequel, titled *Rise of an Empire*, based on Miller's previously unpublished graphic novel prequel *Xerxes*, was released on March 7, 2014.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Dilios, a hoplite in the Spartan army, narrates the story of a Spartan king named Leonidas I from childhood to kingship through the Spartan child-rearing system and the Battle of Thermopylae.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] A Persian herald arrives at Sparta one day, urging Leonidas to present an offering of "earth and water" as a token of submission to King Xerxes.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Leonidas and the Spartan soldiers decline, throwing the herald, who insulted Queen Gorgo, and his envoy into a bottomless pit.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Visiting the Ephors, Leonidas proposes driving back the Persians through Thermopylae by funneling them into a narrow pass, giving the Greeks' heavy infantry the advantage over the numerically superior Persian light infantry.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The Ephors warn Leonidas that Sparta should not wage war during the upcoming Carneia and consult the Oracle, who corroborates their advice.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] As Leonidas angrily departs, an agent from Xerxes appears alongside a Spartan politician, Theron, rewarding the Ephors for their covert support with gold and "fresh oracles".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Having been denied permission to mobilize Sparta's army, Leonidas gathers 300 soldiers, with many of them leaving behind sons to carry on their name.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Theron and the Council confront Leonidas and his men about defying the Ephors.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Leonidas denies going to war, yet they depart for the Hot Gates shortly afterwards.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Joined by a few thousand Arcadians and their leader Daxos along with other Greeks, they discover a village that was pillaged by the Persians, leaving no one alive, and reach Thermopylae, watching a storm sinking many Persian navy ships at the Aegean Sea.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The Spartans then scout out a large Persian encampment and construct a wall using the bodies of slain Persian scouts.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Meanwhile, Leonidas encounters Ephialtes, a deformed Spartan whose parents fled Sparta to spare him certain infanticide.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Ephialtes warns him of a secret goat path the Persians could use to outflank and surround the Spartans.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Looking to redeem his family name, Ephialtes requests he join Leonidas's army.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Although sympathetic and despite Ephialtes skilled thrust attack, Leonidas rejects as he could not raise his shield, as it would compromise their phalanx formation.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The battle begins soon after the Spartans' refusal to lay down their weapons.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Using the narrowed pathway, the Spartans repel many waves of the advancing Persian infantry and cavalry, suffering no casualties, even a Persian arrow volley was no use.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Xerxes, impressed by the Spartans skills, personally approaches Leonidas and offers him immense wealth and power, and control of all the Greek forces, if he surrenders.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Leonidas declines, mocking the inferior quality of Xerxes' warriors.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Xerxes sends in his elite guard, the Immortals, accompanied by the monstrous Über Immortal, but the Greeks once again triumph, suffering only a few Spartan casualties.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] On the second day, Xerxes unsuccessfully dispatches new waves of armies against the Spartans, including Slaves forced into the fight, war elephants, bombardiers, and an armored rhinoceros.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Xerxes becomes irate to the point where he starts executing his own generals for their failures.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Meanwhile, an embittered Ephialtes, having defected to Xerxes, reveals the secret path in exchange for wealth, women, and a uniform.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] During the fight, Leonidas' loyal captain and friend Artemis suffers a personal tragedy when his eldest son Astinos is decapitated, compelling him to break formation and kill a group of Persians in a vengeful rage.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The Arcadians retreat upon learning of Ephialtes' betrayal, but the Spartans choose to stay.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Leonidas orders an injured but reluctant Dilios to return to Sparta and inform his compatriots of what has happened.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Enraged, Gorgo kills Theron, revealing a bag of Xerxes' gold in his robe.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Acknowledging his betrayal, the Council unanimously agrees to send reinforcements.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] On the third day, the Persians, led by Ephialtes, traverse the secret path, encircling the Spartans.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Xerxes' general again demands their surrender even as Ephialtes begs for Leonidas to do so, but the Spartans refuse, as Leonidas tells Ephialtes "May You Live Forever!" and a young Spartan soldier named Stelios kills the general.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Angered, Xerxes orders his troops to attack.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Leonidas throws his spear at Xerxes, slicing his face to prove the God-King's mortality.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Leonidas and the remaining Spartans fight to the last man until they finally succumb to an arrow barrage.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Inspired by Leonidas' sacrifice and Dilios' testimony before the Spartan Council, the Greeks mobilize an army, with Dilios heading the Spartan-led charge.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] After delivering a rousing emotional speech honoring King Leonidas and the 300 who sacrificed their lives a year prior, Dilios leads the Greeks into the Battle of Plataea against the Persians.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Producer Gianni Nunnari was not the only person planning a film about the Battle of Thermopylae, as director Michael Mann had already planned a film of the battle based on the book *Gates of Fire*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Nunnari discovered Frank Miller's graphic novel *300*, which impressed him enough to acquire the film rights.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] *300* was jointly produced by Nunnari and Mark Canton while Michael B.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Director Zack Snyder was hired in June 2004 as he had attempted to make a film based on Miller's novel before making his debut with the remake of *Dawn of the Dead*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Snyder then had screenwriter Kurt Johnstad rewrite Gordon's script for production and Frank Miller was retained as consultant and executive producer.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Frank Miller's original graphic novel *300* was inspired by the film *The 300 Spartans*, which Miller first saw at age six.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The film is a shot-for-shot adaptation of the comic book, similar to the 2005 film adaptation of *Sin City*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Snyder photocopied panels from the comic book, from which he planned the preceding and succeeding shots.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] "It was a fun process for me... to have a frame as a goal to get to", he said.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Like the comic book, the adaptation also used the character Dilios as a narrator.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Snyder used this narrative technique to show the audience that the surreal "Frank Miller world" of *300* was told from a subjective perspective.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] By using Dilios' gift of storytelling, he was able to introduce fantasy elements into the film, explaining that "Dilios is a guy who knows how not to wreck a good story with truth".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Snyder also added the subplot in which Queen Gorgo attempts to rally support for Leonidas.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Two months of pre-production were required to create hundreds of shields, spears and swords, some of which were recycled from *Troy* and *Alexander*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Creatures were designed by Jordu Schell, and an animatronic wolf and thirteen animatronic horses were created.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The actors trained alongside the stuntmen, and even Snyder joined in.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Upwards of 600 costumes were created for the film, as well as extensive prosthetics for various characters and the corpses of Persian soldiers.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Shaun Smith and Mark Rappaport worked hand in hand with Snyder in pre-production to design the look of the individual characters, and to produce the prosthetic makeup effects, props, weapons and dummy bodies required for the production.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Post-production was handled by Montreal's Meteor Studios and Hybride Technologies filled in the bluescreen footage with more than 1,500 visual effects shots.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Visual effects supervisor Chris Watts and production designer Jim Bissell created a process dubbed "The Crush", which allowed the Meteor artists to manipulate the colors by increasing the contrast of light and dark.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Certain sequences were desaturated and tinted to establish different moods.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Ghislain St-Pierre, who led the team of artists, described the effect: "Everything looks realistic, but it has a kind of a gritty illustrative feel." Various computer programs, including Maya, RenderMan, and RealFlow, were used to create the "spraying blood".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The post-production lasted for a year and was handled by a total of ten special effects companies.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] In July 2005, composer Tyler Bates began work on the film, describing the score as having "beautiful themes on the top and large choir", but "tempered with some extreme heaviness".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The composer had scored for a test scene that the director wanted to show to Warner Bros. to illustrate the path of the project.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Bates said that the score had "a lot of weight and intensity in the low end of the percussion" that Snyder found agreeable to the film.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The score was recorded at Abbey Road Studios and features the vocals of Azam Ali.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] A standard edition and a special edition of the soundtrack containing 25 tracks was released on March 6, 2007, with the special edition containing a 16-page booklet and three two-sided trading cards.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The score has caused some controversy in the film composer community, garnering criticism for its striking similarity to several other recent soundtracks, including James Horner and Gabriel Yared's work for the film *Troy*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The heaviest borrowings are said to be from Elliot Goldenthal's 1999 score for *Titus*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] "Remember Us", from *300*, is identical in parts to the "Finale" from *Titus*, and "Returns a King" is similar to the cue "Victorius Titus".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The official *300* website was launched by Warner Bros. in December 2005.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The "conceptual art" and Zack Snyder's production blog were the initial attractions of the site.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Later, the website added video journals describing production details, including comic-to-screen shots and the creatures of *300*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] In January 2007, the studio launched a MySpace page for the film.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The Art Institutes created a micro-site to promote the film.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] At San Diego Comic-Con in July 2006, the *300* panel aired a promotional teaser trailer of the film, which was positively received.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Despite stringent security, the trailer was subsequently leaked on the Internet.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Warner Bros. released the official trailer for *300* on October 4, 2006, and later on it made its debut on Apple.com where it received considerable exposure.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The background music used in the trailers was "Just Like You Imagined" by Nine Inch Nails.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] A second *300* trailer, which was attached to *Apocalypto*, was released in theaters on December 8, 2006, and online the day before.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] On January 22, 2007, an exclusive trailer for the film was broadcast during prime-time television.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The trailers have been credited with igniting interest in the film and contributing to its box-office success.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Interactive Entertainment announced its intention to make a PlayStation Portable game, *300: March to Glory*, based on the film.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Collision Studios worked with Warner Bros. to capture the style of the film in the video game, which was released simultaneously with the film in the United States.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The National Entertainment Collectibles Association produced a series of action figures based on the film, as well as replicas of weapons and armor.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Warner Bros. promoted *300* by sponsoring the Ultimate Fighting Championship's light heavyweight champion Chuck Liddell, who made personal appearances and participated in other promotional activities.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The studio also joined with the National Hockey League to produce a 30-second TV spot promoting the film in tandem with the Stanley Cup playoffs.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] In August 2006, Warner Bros. announced *300*'s release date as March 16, 2007, but in October the release was moved forward to March 9, 2007.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] An unfinished cut of *300* was shown at Butt-Numb-A-Thon film festival on December 9, 2006.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] On July 9, 2007, American cable channel TNT bought the rights to broadcast the film from Warner Bros.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] TNT started airing the film in September 2009.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Sources say that the network paid between $17 million and just under $20 million for the broadcasting rights.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] TNT agreed to a three-year deal instead of the more typical five-year deal.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The film received a standing ovation at its world premiere in front of 1,700 audience members at the Berlin International Film Festival on February 14, 2007.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] It had been panned at a press screening hours earlier, where many attendees left during the showing and those who remained booed at the end.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] As of July 2024, on Rotten Tomatoes, the film had an approval rating of 61% based on 238 reviews, with an average rating of 6.10/10.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The site's critical consensus reads, "A simple-minded but visually exciting experience, full of blood, violence, and ready-made movie quotes." As of October 2020, on Metacritic, the film had a weighted average score of 52 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating "mixed or average" reviews.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Audiences polled by CinemaScore gave the film an average grade of "A−" on an A+ to F scale.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Some of the most unfavorable reviews came from major American newspapers.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Kenneth Turan wrote in the *Los Angeles Times* that "unless you love violence as much as a Spartan, Quentin Tarantino or a video-game-playing teenage boy, you will not be endlessly fascinated".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Roger Ebert gave the film a 2 out of 4 rating, writing that "*300* has one-dimensional caricatures who talk like professional wrestlers plugging their next feud".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Some critics employed at Greek newspapers have been particularly critical, such as film critic Robby Eksiel, who said that moviegoers would be dazzled by the "digital action" but also feel irritated by the "pompous interpretations and one-dimensional characters".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] At the 2007 MTV Movie Awards, *300* was nominated for Best Movie, Best Performance for Gerard Butler, Best Breakthrough Performance for Lena Headey, Best Villain for Rodrigo Santoro, and Best Fight for Leonidas battling "the Über Immortal", but only won the award for Best Fight.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] *300* won both the Best Dramatic Film and Best Action Film honors in the 2006–2007 Golden Icon Awards presented by Travolta Family Entertainment.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] In December 2007, *300* won *IGN*'s Movie of the Year 2007, along with Best Comic Book Adaptation and King Leonidas as Favorite Character.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The movie received 10 nominations for the 2008 Saturn Awards, winning the awards for Best Director and Best Action/Adventure/Thriller Film.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] In 2009, *National Review* magazine ranked *300* number five on its 25 "Best Conservative Movies of the Last 25 Years" list.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] In the actual Battle of Thermopylae, the Spartans had already joined an alliance with other Greek poleis against the Persians.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] During the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes's invasion of Greece coincided with a Spartan religious festival, the Carneia, in which the Spartans were not permitted to make war.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Still, realizing the threat of the Persians and not wanting to appear as Persian sympathizers, the Spartan government, rather than Leonidas alone, decided to send Leonidas with his personal 300-strong bodyguard to Thermopylae.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Other Greek poleis joined the 300 Spartan men and totaled somewhere between 5,000 and 6,000 total Greek troops.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The historical consensus among both ancient chroniclers and current scholars was that Thermopylae was a clear Greek defeat, and the Persian invasion would be pushed back only in later ground and naval battles.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Since few records on the actual martial arts used by the Spartans survive aside from accounts of formations and tactics, the fight choreography, led by the stunt coordinator and fight choreographer Damon Caro, was a synthesis of different weapon arts with Filipino martial arts as the base.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Paul Cartledge, Professor of Greek History at Cambridge University, advised the filmmakers on the pronunciation of Greek names and said that they "made good use" of his published work on Sparta.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] He praised the film for its portrayal of "the Spartans' heroic code" and of "the key role played by women in backing up, indeed reinforcing, the male martial code of heroic honour", but he expressed reservations about its "'West' (goodies) vs 'East' (baddies) polarization".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Cartledge wrote that he enjoyed the film but found Leonidas' description of the Athenians as "boy lovers" ironic since the Spartans themselves incorporated institutional pederasty into their educational system.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Ephraim Lytle, assistant professor of Hellenistic history at the University of Toronto, said that *300* selectively idealized Spartan society in a "problematic and disturbing" fashion and portrayed the "hundred nations of the Persians" as monsters and non-Spartan Greeks as weak.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] He suggested that the film's moral universe would have seemed "as bizarre to ancient Greeks as it does to modern historians".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Lytle also commented, "Ephialtes, who betrays the Greeks, is likewise changed from a local Malian of sound body into a Spartan outcast, a grotesquely disfigured troll who by Spartan custom should have been left exposed as an infant to die.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Leonidas points out that his hunched back means Ephialtes cannot lift his shield high enough to fight in the phalanx.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] He remarked that Simonides, Aeschylus, and Herodotus viewed Thermopylae as a battle against "Eastern centralism and collective serfdom", which opposed "the idea of the free citizen of an autonomous polis".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] He also said that the film portrays the battle in a "surreal" manner and that the intent was to "entertain and shock first, and instruct second".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Robert McHenry, the former editor-in-chief of *Encyclopædia Britannica* and the author of *How to Know*, said that the film "is an almost ineffably silly movie.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Stills from the film could easily be used to promote *Buns of Steel*, or AbMaster, or ThighMaster.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Snyder stated in an MTV interview that "the events are 90 percent accurate.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] It's just in the visualization that it's crazy....
[src:bob-barker/300-film] I've shown this movie to world-class historians who have said it's amazing.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] They can't believe it's as accurate as it is." Nevertheless, he also said the film is "an opera, not a documentary.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] That's what I say when people say it's historically inaccurate." He was also quoted in a BBC News story as saying that the film is, at its core "a fantasy film".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] He also describes the film's narrator, Dilios, as "a guy who knows how not to wreck a good story with truth".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] In an interview, Miller stated, "The inaccuracies, almost all of them, are intentional.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] I took those chest plates and leather skirts off of them for a reason.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] I wanted these guys to move and I wanted 'em to look good.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] I knocked their helmets off a fair amount, partly so you can recognize who the characters are.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Spartans, in full regalia, were almost indistinguishable except at a very close angle.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Another liberty I took was, they all had plumes, but I only gave a plume to Leonidas, to make him stand out and identify him as a king.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] I was looking for more an evocation than a history lesson.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The best result I can hope for is that if the movie excites someone, they'll go explore the histories themselves.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Kaveh Farrokh, in the paper "The 300 Movie: Separating Fact from Fiction", noted that the film falsely portrayed "the Greco-Persian Wars in binary terms: the democratic, good, rational 'Us' versus the tyrannical, evil and irrational, 'other' of the ever-nebulous (if not exotic) 'Persia'".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] He highlighted three points regarding the contribution of the Achaemenid Empire to the creation of democracy and human rights: "The founder of the Achaemenid Empire, Cyrus the Great, was the world's first emperor to openly declare and guarantee the sanctity of human rights and individual freedom....
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Cyrus was a follower of the teachings of Zoroaster, the founder of one of the world's oldest monotheistic religions....
[src:bob-barker/300-film] When Cyrus defeated King Nabonidus of Babylon, he officially declared the freedom of the Jews from their Babylonian captivity.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] This was the first time in history that a world power had guaranteed the survival of the Jewish people, religion, customs and culture." He abolished slavery.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Before the release of *300*, Warner Bros. expressed concerns about the political aspects of the film's theme.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Snyder relates that there was "a huge sensitivity about East versus West with the studio".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Media speculation about a possible parallel between the Greco-Persian conflict and current events began in an interview with Snyder that was conducted before the Berlin Film Festival.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The interviewer remarked that "everyone is sure to be translating this [film] into contemporary politics".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Snyder replied that he was aware that people would read the film through the lens of current events, but no parallels the film and the modern world were intended.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Outside current political parallels, some critics have raised more general questions about the film's ideological orientation.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] *Slate*'s Dana Stevens compared the film to *The Eternal Jew* (1940) "as a textbook example of how race-baiting fantasy and nationalist myth can serve as an incitement to total war.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Indeed, the Lambda sign on the Spartans' shields in *300* formed the inspiration for the official symbol of the far-right Identitarian movement.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The writer Frank Miller said: "The Spartans were a paradoxical people.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] They were the biggest slave owners in Greece.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] But at the same time, Spartan women had an unusual level of rights.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] It's a paradox that they were a bunch of people who in many ways were fascist, but they were the bulwark against the fall of democracy.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The closest comparison you can draw in terms of our own military today is to think of the red-caped Spartans as being like our special-ops forces.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] They're these almost superhuman characters with a tremendous warrior ethic, who were unquestionably the best fighters in Greece.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] I didn't want to render Sparta in overly accurate terms, because ultimately I do want you to root for the Spartans.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] I couldn't show them being quite as cruel as they were.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Chemers, author of "'With Your Shield, or on It': Disability Representation in *300*" in the *Disability Studies Quarterly*, said that the film's portrayal of the hunchback and his story "is not mere ableism: this is anti-disability".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Frank Miller, commenting on areas in which he lessened the Spartan cruelty for narrative purposes, said: "I have King Leonidas very gently tell Ephialtes, the hunchback, that they can't use him [as a soldier], because of his deformity.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] From its opening, *300* also attracted controversy over its portrayal of Persians.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Officials of the Iranian government denounced the film.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Some scenes in the film portray demon-like and other fictional creatures as part of the Persian army, and the fictionalized portrayal of Persian King Xerxes I has been criticised as effeminate.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Critics suggested that it was meant to stand in stark contrast to the portrayed masculinity of the Spartan army.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Steven Rea argued that the film's Persians were a vehicle for an anachronistic cross-section of Western aspirational stereotypes of Asian and African cultures.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The film's portrayal of ancient Persians caused a particularly strong reaction in Iran.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Various Iranian officials condemned the film.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The Iranian Academy of the Arts submitted a formal complaint against the film to UNESCO that called it an attack on the historical identity of Iran.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The Iranian mission to the United Nations protested the film in a press release, and Iranian embassies protested its screening in France, Thailand, Turkey, and Uzbekistan.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The film was banned in Iran, with it being considered American propaganda.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Reviewers in the United States and elsewhere "noted the political overtones of the West-against-Iran story line and the way Persians are depicted as decadent, sexually flamboyant and evil in contrast to the noble Greeks".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] With black market copies of the film already available in Tehran with the film's international release and news of the film's surprising success at the US box office, the film prompted widespread anger in Iran.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Azadeh Moaveni of *Time* reported, "All of Tehran was outraged.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Everywhere I went yesterday, the talk vibrated with indignation over the film." Newspapers in Iran featured headlines such as "Hollywood Declares War on Iranians" and "300 Against 70 Million", the latter being the size of Iran's population.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The cultural advisor to Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad called the film an "American attempt for psychological warfare against Iran".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Moaveni identified two factors that may have contributed to the intensity of Iranian indignation over the film.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Firstly, she described the timing of the film's release, on the eve of Nowruz, the Persian New Year, as "inauspicious".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Secondly, Iranians tend to view the era depicted in the film as "a particularly noble page in their history".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Moaveni suggested that *300*'s box office success compared with *Alexander*'s failure (another spurious period epic dealing with Persians), was "cause for considerable alarm, signaling ominous U.S. intentions".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] According to *The Guardian*, Iranian critics of *300*, ranging from bloggers to government officials, described the movie "as a calculated attempt to demonise Iran at a time of intensifying U.S. pressure over the country's nuclear programme".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] An Iranian government spokesman described the film as "hostile behavior which is the result of cultural and psychological warfare".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Moaveni reported that the Iranians with whom she interacted were "adamant that the movie was secretly funded by the U.S. government to prepare Americans for going to war against Iran".
[src:bob-barker/300-film] In June 2008, producers Mark Canton, Gianni Nunnari and Bernie Goldmann revealed that work had begun on a sequel to *300*, *300: Rise of an Empire*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Legendary Pictures had announced that Frank Miller had started writing the follow-up graphic novel and that Zack Snyder was interested in directing the adaptation but moved on to develop and direct the Superman reboot and DC Extended Universe first installment *Man of Steel*.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] Noam Murro directed instead, while Zack Snyder produced.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The film focused on the Athenian admiral, Themistocles, as portrayed by Australian actor Sullivan Stapleton.
[src:bob-barker/300-film] The sequel, *300: Rise of an Empire*, was released on March 7, 2014, and achieved box office success with $337 million grossed worldwide from a budget of $110 million, despite receiving mixed reviews.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] The **34th Daytime Emmy Awards**, commemorating excellence in American daytime programming from 2006, was held on June 15, 2007 at the Kodak Theatre in Los Angeles, California.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] CBS televised the ceremonies in the United States, their last time doing so as of 2017.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] Meanwhile, Creative Arts Emmy Awards were presented one day earlier on June 14 at the Hollywood and Highland Ballroom.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] Nominations for the children's series categories were announced on February 7, 2007.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] The rest of the nominations were released on March 14.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] The "Service Show" award categories were renamed the "Lifestyle" categories.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] Also a new award for Outstanding Morning Programming debuted.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] The Creative Arts Awards were held the day before the regular ceremony.
[src:bob-barker/34th-daytime-emmy-awards] A first-place tie was recorded in this category.
[src:bob-barker/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:bob-barker/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:bob-barker/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:bob-barker/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:bob-barker/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:bob-barker/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:bob-barker/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:bob-barker/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:bob-barker/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:bob-barker/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:bob-barker/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:bob-barker/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:bob-barker/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:bob-barker/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL was at one point the most recognized brand on the Web in the United States.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL once provided a dial-up Internet service to millions of Americans and pioneered chat rooms and instant messaging with AOL Instant Messenger (AIM).
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 1998, AOL purchased Netscape for US$4.2 billion.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] By 2000, AOL was providing internet service to over 20 million consumers, dominating the market of internet service providers (ISPs).
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 2001, at the height of its popularity, it purchased the media conglomerate Time Warner in the largest merger in US history.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL shrank rapidly thereafter, partly due to the decline of dial-up and rise of broadband.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL was spun off from Time Warner in 2009, with Tim Armstrong appointed the new CEO.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Under his leadership, the company invested in media brands and advertising technologies.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 2015, AOL was acquired by Verizon Communications for $4.4 billion, and was merged with Yahoo! the following year after the latter was also acquired by Verizon.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In May 2021, Verizon announced it would sell Verizon Media (and thus AOL) to private equity firm Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, and the sale was completed at the end of August.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In October 2025, Apollo reached a $1.5 billion deal to sell AOL to the Italian conglomerate Bending Spoons.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL began in 1983, as a short-lived venture called **Control Video Corporation** (**CVC**), founded by William von Meister.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Its sole product was an online service called GameLine for the Atari 2600 video game console, after von Meister's idea of buying music on demand was rejected by Warner Communications.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Subscribers bought a modem from the company for $49.95 and paid a one-time $15 setup fee.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] GameLine permitted subscribers to temporarily download games and keep track of high scores, at a cost of $1 per game.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The telephone disconnected and the downloaded game would remain in GameLine's Master Module, playable until the user turned off the console or downloaded another game.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In January 1983, Steve Case was hired as a marketing consultant for Control Video on the recommendation of his brother, investment banker Dan Case.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In May 1983, Jim Kimsey became a manufacturing consultant for Control Video, which was near bankruptcy.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Kimsey was brought in by his West Point friend Frank Caufield, an investor in the company.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In early 1985, von Meister left the company.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On May 24, 1985, **Quantum Computer Services**, an online services company, was founded by Kimsey from the remnants of Control Video, with Kimsey as chief executive officer and Marc Seriff as chief technology officer.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The technical team consisted of Seriff, Tom Ralston, Ray Heinrich, Steve Trus, Ken Huntsman, Janet Hunter, Dave Brown, Craig Dykstra, Doug Coward, and Mike Ficco.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 1987, Case was promoted again to executive vice-president.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Kimsey soon began to groom Case to take over the role of CEO, which he did when Kimsey retired in 1991.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Kimsey changed the company's strategy, and in 1985, launched a dedicated online service for Commodore 64 and 128 computers, originally called Quantum Link ("Q-Link" for short).
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The Quantum Link software was based on software licensed from PlayNet, Inc., which was founded in 1983 by Howard Goldberg and Dave Panzl.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The service was different from other online services as it used the computing power of the Commodore 64 and the Apple II rather than just a "dumb" terminal.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] It passed tokens back and forth and provided a fixed-price service tailored for home users.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In May 1988, Quantum and Apple launched AppleLink Personal Edition for Apple II and Macintosh computers.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In August 1988, Quantum launched PC Link, a service for IBM-compatible PCs developed in a joint venture with the Tandy Corporation.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] After the company parted ways with Apple in October 1989, Quantum changed the service's name to America Online.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Case promoted and sold AOL as the online service for people unfamiliar with computers, in contrast to CompuServe, which was well established in the technical community.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] From the beginning, AOL included online games in its mix of products; many classic and casual games were included in the original PlayNet software system.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In February 1991, AOL for IBM PC compatibles running MS-DOS was launched using a GeoWorks interface; it was followed a year later by AOL for Windows 3.0.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This coincided with growth in pay-based online services, like Prodigy, CompuServe, and GEnie.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] During the early 1990s, the average subscription lasted for about 25 months and accounted for $350 in total revenue.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Advertisements invited modem owners to "Try America Online FREE", promising free software and trial membership.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL discontinued Q-Link and PC Link in late 1994.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In September 1993, AOL added Usenet access to its features.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This is commonly referred to as the "Eternal September", as Usenet's cycle of new users was previously dominated by smaller numbers of college and university freshmen gaining access in September and taking a few weeks to acclimate.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This also coincided with a new "carpet bombing" marketing campaign by CMO Jan Brandt to distribute as many free trial AOL trial disks as possible through nonconventional distribution partners.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] At one point, 50% of the CDs produced worldwide had an AOL logo.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL quickly surpassed GEnie, and by the mid-1990s, it passed Prodigy (which for several years allowed AOL advertising) and CompuServe.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In November 1994, AOL purchased Booklink for its web browser, to give its users web access.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 1996, AOL replaced Booklink with a browser based on Internet Explorer, reportedly in exchange for inclusion of AOL in Windows.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL purchased search engine WebCrawler in 1995, but sold it to Excite the following year; the deal made Excite the sole search and directory service on AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] After the deal closed in March 1997, AOL launched its own branded search engine, based on Excite, called NetFind.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL charged its users an hourly fee until December 1996, when the company changed to a flat monthly rate of $19.95.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] During this time, AOL connections were flooded with users trying to connect, and many canceled their accounts due to constant busy signals.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] A commercial was made featuring Steve Case telling people AOL was working day and night to fix the problem.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Within three years, AOL's user base grew to 10 million people.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 1995, AOL was headquartered at 8619 Westwood Center Drive in the Tysons Corner CDP in unincorporated Fairfax County, Virginia in the Washington, D.C. metropolitan area. near the Town of Vienna.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL was quickly running out of room in October 1996 for its network at the Fairfax County campus.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In mid-1996, AOL moved to 22000 AOL Way in Dulles, unincorporated Loudoun County, Virginia to provide room for future growth.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In a five-year landmark agreement with the most popular operating system, AOL was bundled with Windows software.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On March 31, 1996, the short-lived eWorld was purchased by AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 1997, about half of all US homes with Internet access had it through AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] During this time, AOL's content channels, under Jason Seiken, including News, Sports, and Entertainment, experienced their greatest growth as AOL become the dominant online service internationally with more than 34 million subscribers.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On August 7, 1996, AOL experienced a total outage starting at 1:00 AM PST that would last nineteen hours and took over six million people offline.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In February 1998, AOL acquired CompuServe Interactive Services (CIS) via WorldCom (later Verizon), which kept Compuware's networking business.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In November 1998, AOL announced it would acquire Netscape, best known for their web browser, in a major $4.2 billion deal.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Another large acquisition in December 1999 was that of MapQuest, for $1.1 billion.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In January 2000, as new broadband technologies were being rolled out around the New York City metropolitan area and elsewhere across the United States, AOL and Time Warner announced plans to merge, forming AOL Time Warner, Inc.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The terms of the deal called for AOL shareholders to own 55% of the new, combined company.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The new company was led by executives from AOL, SBI, and Time Warner.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Gerald Levin, who had served as CEO of Time Warner, was CEO of the new company.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Michael Kelly (from AOL) was the chief financial officer, Robert W.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Pittman (from AOL) and Dick Parsons (from Time Warner) served as co-chief operating officers.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 2002, Jonathan Miller became CEO of AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The following year, AOL Time Warner dropped the "AOL" from its name.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] It was the largest merger in history when completed with the combined value of the companies at $360 billion.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This value fell sharply, to as low as $120 billion, as markets repriced AOL's valuation as a pure internet firm more modestly when combined with the traditional media and cable business.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This status did not last long, and the company's value rose again within three months.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] By the end of that year, the tide had turned against "pure" internet companies, with many collapsing under falling stock prices, and even the strongest companies in the field losing up to 75% of their market value.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The decline continued through 2001, but even with the losses, AOL was among the internet giants that continued to outperform brick and mortar companies.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 2004, along with the launch of AOL 9.0 Optimized, AOL also made available the option of personalized greetings which would enable the user to hear his or her name while accessing basic functions and mail alerts, or while logging in or out.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 2005, AOL broadcast the Live 8 concert live over the Internet, and thousands of users downloaded clips of the concert over the following months.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In late 2005, AOL released AOL Safety & Security Center, a bundle of McAfee Antivirus, CA anti-spyware, and proprietary firewall and phishing protection software.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] News reports in late 2005 identified companies such as Yahoo!, Microsoft, and Google as candidates for turning AOL into a joint venture.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Those plans were abandoned when it was revealed on December 20, 2005, that Google would purchase a 5% share of AOL for $1 billion.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On April 3, 2006, AOL announced that it would retire the full name America Online.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The official name of the service became AOL, and the full name of the Time Warner subdivision became AOL LLC.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On June 8, 2006, AOL offered a new program called AOL Active Security Monitor, a diagnostic tool to monitor and rate PC security status, and recommended additional security software from AOL or Download.com.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Two months later, AOL released AOL Active Virus Shield, a free product developed by Kaspersky Lab, that did not require an AOL account, only an internet email address.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The ISP side of AOL UK was bought by Carphone Warehouse in October 2006 to take advantage of its 100,000 LLU customers, making Carphone Warehouse the largest LLU provider in the UK.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In August 2006, AOL announced that it would offer email accounts and software previously available only to its paying customers, provided that users accessed AOL or AOL.com through an access method not owned by AOL (otherwise known as "third party transit", "bring your own access" or "BYOA").
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The move was designed to reduce costs associated with the "walled garden" business model by reducing usage of AOL-owned access points and shifting members with high-speed internet access from client-based usage to the more lucrative advertising provider AOL.com.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The change from paid to free access was also designed to slow the rate at which members canceled their accounts and defected to Microsoft Hotmail, Yahoo! or other free email providers.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Also in August, AOL informed its US customers of an increase in the price of its dial-up access to $25.90.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The increase was part of an effort to migrate the service's remaining dial-up users to broadband, as the increased price was the same as that of its monthly DSL access.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] However, AOL subsequently began offering unlimited dial-up access for $9.95 a month.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On November 16, 2006, Randy Falco succeeded Jonathan Miller as CEO.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In December 2006, AOL closed its last remaining call center in the United States, "taking the America out of America Online," according to industry pundits.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Service centers based in India and the Philippines continue to provide customer support and technical assistance to subscribers.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On September 17, 2007, AOL announced the relocation of one of its corporate headquarters from Dulles, Virginia to New York City and the combination of its advertising units into a new subsidiary called Platform A.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This action followed several advertising acquisitions, most notably Advertising.com, and highlighted the company's new focus on advertising-driven business models.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL management stressed that "significant operations" would remain in Dulles, which included the company's access services and modem banks.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In October 2007, AOL announced the relocation of its other headquarters from Loudoun County, Virginia to New York City, while continuing to operate its Virginia offices.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] As part of the move to New York and the restructuring of responsibilities at the Dulles headquarters complex after the Reston move, Falco announced on October 15, 2007, plans to lay off 2,000 employees worldwide by the end of 2007, beginning "immediately".
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The result was a layoff of approximately 40% of AOL's employees.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Most compensation packages associated with the October 2007 layoffs included a minimum of 120 days of severance pay, 60 of which were offered in lieu of the 60-day advance notice requirement by provisions of the 1988 federal WARN Act.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] By November 2007, AOL's customer base had been reduced to 10.1 million subscribers, slightly more than the number of subscribers of Comcast and AT&T Yahoo!.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] According to Falco, as of December 2007, the conversion rate of accounts from paid access to free access was more than 80%.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On January 3, 2008, AOL announced the closing of its Reston, Virginia, data center, which was sold to CRG West.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On February 6, Time Warner CEO Jeff Bewkes announced that Time Warner would divide AOL's internet-access and advertising businesses, with the possibility of later selling the internet-access division.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On March 13, 2008, AOL purchased the social networking site Bebo for $850 million (£417 million).
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On July 25, AOL announced that it was shuttering Xdrive, AOL Pictures and BlueString to save on costs and focus on its core advertising business.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On October 31, AOL Hometown (a web-hosting service for the websites of AOL customers) and the AOL Journal blog hosting service were eliminated.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On March 12, 2009, Tim Armstrong, formerly with Google, was named chairman and CEO of AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On May 28, Time Warner announced that it would position AOL as an independent company after Google's shares ceased at the end of the fiscal year.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On November 23, AOL unveiled a new brand identity with the wordmark "Aol." superimposed onto canvases created by commissioned artists.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The new identity, designed by Wolff Olins, was integrated with all of AOL's services on December 10, the date upon which AOL traded independently for the first time since the Time Warner merger on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On April 6, 2010, AOL announced plans to shutter or sell Bebo.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On June 16, the property was sold to Criterion Capital Partners for an undisclosed amount, believed to be approximately $10 million.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In December, AIM eliminated access to AOL chat rooms, noting a marked decline in usage in recent months.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Under Armstrong's leadership, AOL followed a new business direction marked by a series of acquisitions.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] It announced the acquisition of Patch Media, a network of community-specific news and information sites focused on towns and communities.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On September 28, 2010, at the San Francisco TechCrunch Disrupt Conference, AOL signed an agreement to acquire TechCrunch.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On December 12, 2010, AOL acquired about.me, a personal profile and identity platform, four days after the platform's public launch.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On January 31, 2011, AOL announced the acquisition of European video distribution network goviral.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In March 2011, AOL acquired *HuffPost* for $315 million.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Shortly after the acquisition was announced, *Huffington Post* co-founder Arianna Huffington replaced AOL content chief David Eun, assuming the role of president and editor-in-chief of the AOL Huffington Post Media Group.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On March 10, AOL announced that it would cut approximately 900 workers following the *HuffPost* acquisition.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On September 14, 2011, AOL formed a strategic ad-selling partnership with two of its largest competitors, Yahoo and Microsoft.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The three companies would begin selling inventory on each other's sites.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The strategy was designed to help the companies compete with Google and advertising networks.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On February 28, 2012, AOL partnered with PBS to launch MAKERS, a digital documentary series focusing on high-achieving women in industries perceived as male-dominated such as war, comedy, space, business, Hollywood and politics.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Subjects for MAKERS episodes have included Oprah Winfrey, Hillary Clinton, Sheryl Sandberg, Martha Stewart, Indra Nooyi, Lena Dunham and Ellen DeGeneres.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On March 15, 2012, AOL announced the acquisition of Hipster, a mobile photo-sharing app, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On April 9, 2012, AOL announced a deal to sell 800 patents to Microsoft for $1.056 billion.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The deal included a perpetual license for AOL to use the patents.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In April, AOL took several steps to expand its ability to generate revenue through online video advertising.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The company announced that it would offer gross rating point (GRP) guarantee for online video, mirroring the television-ratings system and guaranteeing audience delivery for online-video advertising campaigns bought across its properties.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This announcement came just days before the Digital Content NewFront (DCNF) a two-week event held by AOL, Google, Hulu, Microsoft, Vevo and Yahoo to showcase the participating sites' digital video offerings.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The DCNF was conducted in advance of the traditional television upfronts in the hope of diverting more advertising money into the digital space.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On April 24, the company launched the AOL On network, a single website for its video output.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In February 2013, AOL reported its fourth quarter revenue of $599.5 million, its first growth in quarterly revenue in eight years.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In August 2013, Armstrong announced that Patch Media would scale back or sell hundreds of its local news sites.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Not long afterward, layoffs began, with up to 500 out of 1,100 positions initially impacted.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On January 15, 2014, Patch Media was spun off, and majority ownership was held by Hale Global.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] By the end of 2014, AOL controlled 0.74% of the global advertising market, well behind industry leader Google's 31.4%.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On January 23, 2014, AOL acquired Gravity, a software startup that tracked users' online behavior and tailored ads and content based on their interests, for $83 million.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The deal, which included approximately 40 Gravity employees and the company's personalization technology, was Armstrong's fourth-largest deal since taking command in 2009.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Later that year, AOL acquired Vidible, a company that developed technology to help websites run video content from other publishers, and help video publishers sell their content to these websites.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The deal, which was announced December 1, 2014, was reportedly worth roughly $50 million.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On July 16, 2014, AOL earned an Emmy nomination for the AOL original series *The Future Starts Here* in the News and Documentary category.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This came days after AOL earned its first Primetime Emmy Award nomination and win for *Park Bench with Steve Buscemi* in the Outstanding Short Form Variety Series.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Created and hosted by Tiffany Shlain, the series focused on humans' relationship with technology and featured episodes such as "The Future of Our Species", "Why We Love Robots" and "A Case for Optimism".
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On May 12, 2015, Verizon announced plans to buy AOL for $50 per share in a deal valued at $4.4 billion.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The transaction was completed on June 23.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Armstrong, who continued to lead the firm following regulatory approval, called the deal the logical next step for AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] "If you look forward five years, you're going to be in a space where there are going to be massive, global-scale networks, and there's no better partner for us to go forward with than Verizon." he said.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] "It's really not about selling the company today.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Analyst David Bank said he thought the deal made sense for Verizon.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The deal will broaden Verizon's advertising sales platforms and increase its video production ability through websites such as *HuffPost*, TechCrunch, and Engadget.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] However, Craig Moffett said it was unlikely the deal would make a big difference to Verizon's bottom line.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL had about two million dial-up subscribers at the time of the buyout.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The announcement caused AOL's stock price to rise 17%, while Verizon's stock price dropped slightly.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Shortly before the Verizon purchase, on April 14, 2015, AOL launched ONE by AOL, a digital marketing programmatic platform that unifies buying channels and audience management platforms to track and optimize campaigns over multiple screens.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Later that year, on September 15, AOL expanded the product with ONE by AOL: Creative, which is geared towards creative and media agencies to similarly connect marketing and ad distribution efforts.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On May 8, 2015, AOL reported its first-quarter revenue of $625.1 million, $483.5 million of which came from advertising and related operations, marking a 7% increase from Q1 2014.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Over that year, the AOL Platforms division saw a 21% increase in revenue, but a drop in adjusted OIBDA due to increased investments in the company's video and programmatic platforms.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On June 29, 2015, AOL announced a deal with Microsoft to take over the majority of its digital advertising business.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Under the pact, as many as 1,200 Microsoft employees involved with the business will be transferred to AOL, and the company will take over the sale of display, video, and mobile ads on various Microsoft platforms in nine countries, including Brazil, Canada, the United States, and the United Kingdom.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Additionally, Google Search will be replaced on AOL properties with Bing—which will display advertising sold by Microsoft.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Both advertising deals are subject to affiliate marketing revenue sharing.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On September 3, 2015, AOL agreed to buy Millennial Media for $238 million.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On October 23, 2015, AOL completed the acquisition.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On October 1, 2015, Go90, a free ad-supported mobile video service aimed at young adult and teen viewers that Verizon owns and AOL oversees and operates, launched its content publicly after months of beta testing.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The initial launch line-up included content from Comedy Central, HuffPost, Nerdist News, Univision News, Vice, ESPN and MTV.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On April 20, 2016, AOL acquired virtual reality studio RYOT to bring immersive 360 degree video and VR content to HuffPost's global audience across desktop, mobile, and apps.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In July 2016, Verizon Communications announced its intent to purchase the core internet business of Yahoo!.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Verizon merged AOL with Yahoo into a new company called "Oath Inc.", which in January 2019 rebranded itself as Verizon Media.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In April 2018, Oath Inc. sold Moviefone to MoviePass Parent Helios and Matheson Analytics.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In November 2020 the *Huffington Post* was sold to BuzzFeed in a stock deal.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On May 3, 2021, Verizon announced it would sell 90 percent of its Verizon Media division to Apollo Global Management for $5 billion, becoming the second independent incarnation of Yahoo Inc.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 2025, AOL ended its dial-up internet service.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In October 2025, Bending Spoons acquired AOL in a deal valued at roughly $1.5 billion.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In a statement, Bending Spoons CEO Luca Ferrari cited AOL's 30 million active users as part of what made the property attractive.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The purchase was quietly completed in January 2026, Bending Spoons then laid off more than 100 AOL employees in February 2026.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL's web ecosystem operates primarily as a content aggregator and digital service portal.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The AOL homepage aggregates news, lifestyle, and entertainment content from major syndicated third-party media wires and partner networks.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In addition to mobile-optimized web experiences, AOL produces mobile applications for its remaining properties and standalone software utilities.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL Mail is AOL's proprietary email client.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] It provides fully integrated webmail services and direct links to news headlines on AOL content sites.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL Plans offers multiple online safety and assistance subscription bundles: identity theft protection, data security tools, and a general online technical assistance service.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] In 2017, a paid internet suite version called AOL Desktop Gold was released, available for $4.99 per month after a trial period.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] It replaced the previous free software tier.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On January 10, 2018, all versions of the original AOL Desktop were shut down so AOL could focus towards AOL Desktop Gold and AOL Shield.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Following the shutdown of AIM, AOL's original legacy chat rooms continued to be accessible through AOL Desktop Gold until the chat system was permanently shut down on December 15, 2020.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] When it owned the Huffington Post, AOL's content ecosystem featured contributors consisting of over 20,000 bloggers, including politicians, celebrities, academics, and policy experts, who contributed on a wide range of topics.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Several major media brands formerly owned by AOL—including Engadget, Autoblog, TechCrunch, and Built by Girls—became part of Verizon Media (now Yahoo) following Verizon's acquisition of AOL in 2015.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Mobile applications and experimental products associated with these eras, such as Alto, Pip, and Vivv, have also been retired.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL previously operated a global portfolio of advertising technologies and services.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] This included data and programmatic solutions handled through its proprietary ad technology stack, ONE by AOL, which was built on acquisitions such as AdapTV (2013), Convertro (2014), Precision Demand (2014), and Vidible (2014).
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] ONE by AOL operated under two separate banners: ONE by AOL for Publishers and ONE by AOL for Advertisers.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] On September 10, 2018, parent company Oath consolidated BrightRoll, One by AOL, and Yahoo Gemini into a unified ad-tech platform named Oath Ad Platforms, which was later rebranded as Yahoo!
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL originally built its user base on Dial-up Internet access.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] While the service retained 2.1 million subscribers in 2015, membership plummeted to a few thousand by 2021 as remaining premium users transitioned to software support packages.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL officially discontinued its legacy dial-up service on September 30, 2025.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) was AOL's flagship proprietary instant-messaging tool launched in 1997.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] At its peak, billions of messages were sent daily across AIM and associated AOL chat properties.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Over time, it lost significant market share to competitors like Google Chat, Facebook Messenger, and text messaging.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] It also included a integrated video-chat tool, AV by AIM.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] AOL discontinued the AIM service on December 15, 2017.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Subsequent iterations shifted back to supporting the 9.X version lines.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Version 9.8 replaced existing Internet Explorer engine dependencies with the CEF engine to mimic modern web-browsing frameworks like Google Chrome.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Version 11 introduced a complete software architecture rewrite while preserving the 9.8 legacy layout.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The freeware software stack was fully deprecated in 2017 in favor of the paid subscription iteration, AOL Desktop Gold.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] Separately, the company maintained the **AOL Toolbar**, a web browser toolbar distributed as a Mozilla plug-in offering immediate web hooks into fundamental AOL platforms.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p01] The toolbar utility was maintained from 2007 until its retirement in 2018.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In its earlier incarnation as a "walled garden" community and service provider, AOL received criticism for its community policies, terms of service, and customer service.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL was known for its direct mailing of CD-ROMs and 3.5-inch floppy disks containing its software.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The disks were distributed in large numbers; at one point, half of the CDs manufactured worldwide had AOL logos on them.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The marketing tactic was criticized for its environmental cost, and AOL CDs were recognized as *PC World*'s most annoying tech product.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL used a system of volunteers to moderate its chat rooms, forums and user communities.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The program dated back to AOL's early days, when it charged by the hour for access and one of its highest billing services was chat.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL provided free access to community leaders in exchange for moderating the chat rooms, and this effectively made chat very cheap to operate, and more lucrative than AOL's other services of the era.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] There were 33,000 community leaders in 1996.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] All community leaders received hours of training and underwent a probationary period.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] While most community leaders moderated chat rooms, some ran AOL communities and controlled their layout and design, with as much as 90% of AOL's content being created or overseen by community managers until 1996.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] By 1996, ISPs were beginning to charge flat rates for unlimited access, which they could do at a profit because they only provided internet access.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Even though AOL would lose money with such a pricing scheme, it was forced by market conditions to offer unlimited access in October 1996.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In order to return to profitability, AOL rapidly shifted its focus from content creation to advertising, resulting in less of a need to carefully moderate every forum and chat room to keep users willing to pay by the minute to remain connected.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] After unlimited access, AOL considered scrapping the program entirely, but continued it with a reduced number of community leaders, with scaled-back roles in creating content.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Although community leaders continued to receive free access, after 1996 they were motivated more by the prestige of the position and the access to moderator tools and restricted areas within AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] By 1999, there were over 15,000 volunteers in the program.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In May 1999, two former volunteers filed a class-action lawsuit alleging AOL violated the Fair Labor Standards Act by treating volunteers like employees.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Volunteers had to apply for the position, commit to working for at least three to four hours a week, fill out timecards and sign a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] On July 22, AOL ended its youth corps, which consisted of 350 underage community leaders.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] At this time, the United States Department of Labor began an investigation into the program, but it came to no conclusions about AOL's practices.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL ended its community leader program on June 8, 2005.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The class action lawsuit dragged on for years, even after AOL ended the program and AOL declined as a major internet company.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In 2010, AOL finally agreed to settle the lawsuit for $15 million.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The community leader program was described as an example of co-production in a 2009 article in *International Journal of Cultural Studies*.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL has faced a number of lawsuits over claims that it has been slow to stop billing customers after their accounts have been canceled, either by the company or the user.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In addition, AOL changed its method of calculating used minutes in response to a class action lawsuit.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Previously, AOL would add 15 seconds to the time a user was connected to the service and round up to the next whole minute (thus, a person who used the service for 12 minutes and 46 seconds would be charged for 14 minutes).
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL claimed this was to account for sign on/sign off time, but because this practice was not made known to its customers, the plaintiffs won (some also pointed out that signing on and off did not always take 15 seconds, especially when connecting via another ISP).
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL disclosed its connection-time calculation methods to all of its customers and credited them with extra free hours.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In addition, the AOL software would notify the user of exactly how long they were connected and how many minutes they were being charged.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL was sued by the Ohio Attorney General in October 2003 for improper billing practices.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL agreed to resolve any consumer complaints filed with the Ohio AG's office.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In December 2006, AOL agreed to provide restitution to Florida consumers to settle the case filed against them by the Florida Attorney General.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Many customers complained that AOL personnel ignored their demands to cancel service and stop billing.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In response to approximately 300 consumer complaints, the New York Attorney General's office began an inquiry of AOL's customer service policies.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The investigation revealed that the company had an elaborate scheme for rewarding employees who purported to retain or "save" subscribers who had called to cancel their Internet service.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In many instances, such retention was done against subscribers' wishes, or without their consent.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Under the scheme, customer service personnel received bonuses worth tens of thousands of dollars if they could successfully dissuade or "save" half of the people who called to cancel service.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] For several years, AOL had instituted minimum retention or "save" percentages, which consumer representatives were expected to meet.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] These bonuses, and the minimum "save" rates accompanying them, had the effect of employees not honoring cancellations, or otherwise making cancellation unduly difficult for consumers.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] On August 24, 2005, America Online agreed to pay $1.25 million to the state of New York and reformed its customer service procedures.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Under the agreement, AOL would no longer require its customer service representatives to meet a minimum quota for customer retention in order to receive a bonus.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] However the agreement only covered people in the state of New York.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] On June 13, 2006, Vincent Ferrari documented his account cancellation phone call in a blog post, stating he had switched to broadband years earlier.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In the recorded phone call, the AOL representative refused to cancel the account unless the 30-year-old Ferrari explained why AOL hours were still being recorded on it.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Ferrari insisted that AOL software was not even installed on the computer.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] When Ferrari demanded that the account be canceled regardless, the AOL representative asked to speak with Ferrari's father, for whom the account had been set up.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] When CNBC reporters tried to have an account on AOL cancelled, they were hung up on immediately and it ultimately took more than 45 minutes to cancel the account.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] On July 19, 2006, AOL's entire retention manual was released on the Internet.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] On August 3, 2006, Time Warner announced that the company would be dissolving AOL's retention centers due to its profits hinging on $1 billion in cost cuts.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The company estimated that it would lose more than six million subscribers over the following year.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Prior to 2006, AOL often sent unsolicited mass direct mail of 31⁄2" floppy disks and CD-ROMs containing their software.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] They were the most frequent user of this marketing tactic, and received criticism for the environmental cost of the campaign.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] According to *PC World*, in the 1990s "you couldn't open a magazine (*PC World* included) or your mailbox without an AOL disk falling out of it".
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The mass distribution of these disks was seen as wasteful by the public and led to protest groups.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] One such was No More AOL CDs, a web-based effort by two IT workers to collect one million disks with the intent to return the disks to AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The website was started in August 2001, and an estimated 410,176 CDs were collected by August 2007 when the project was shut down.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In 2000, AOL was served with an $8 billion lawsuit alleging that its AOL 5.0 software caused significant difficulties for users attempting to use third-party Internet service providers.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The lawsuit sought damages of up to $1000 for each user that had downloaded the software cited at the time of the lawsuit.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL later agreed to a settlement of $15 million, without admission of wrongdoing.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The AOL software then was given a feature called AOL Dialer, or AOL Connect on Mac OS X.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] This feature allowed users to connect to the ISP without running the full interface.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] This allowed users to use only the applications they wish to use, especially if they do not favor the AOL Browser.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL 9.0 was once identified by Stopbadware as being *under investigation* for installing additional software without disclosure, and modifying browser preferences, toolbars, and icons.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] However, as of the release of AOL 9.0 VR (Vista Ready) on January 26, 2007, it was no longer considered badware due to changes AOL made in the software.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] When AOL gave clients access to Usenet in 1993, they hid at least one newsgroup in standard list view: *alt.aol-sucks*.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL did list the newsgroup in the alternative description view, but changed the description to "Flames and complaints about America Online".
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] With AOL clients swarming Usenet newsgroups, the old, existing user base started to develop a strong distaste for both AOL and its clients, referring to the new state of affairs as Eternal September.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL discontinued access to Usenet on June 25, 2005.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] No official details were provided as to the cause of decommissioning Usenet access, except providing users the suggestion to access Usenet services from a third-party, Google Groups.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL then provided community-based message boards in lieu of Usenet.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL has a detailed set of guidelines and expectations for users on their service, known as the Terms of Service (TOS, also known as Conditions of Service (COS) in the UK).
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] It is separated into three different sections: *Member Agreement*, *Community Guidelines* and *Privacy Policy*.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] All three agreements are presented to users at time of registration and digital acceptance is achieved when they access the AOL service.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] During the period when volunteer chat room hosts and board monitors were used, chat room hosts were given a brief online training session and test on Terms of Service violations.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] There have been many complaints over rules that govern an AOL user's conduct.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Some users disagree with the TOS, citing the guidelines are too strict to follow coupled with the fact the TOS may change without users being made aware.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] A considerable cause for this was likely due to alleged censorship of user-generated content during the earlier years of growth for AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] This decision drew fire from MoveOn, which characterized the program as an "email tax", and the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF), which characterized it as a shakedown of non-profits.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] A website called Dearaol.com was launched, with an online petition and a blog that garnered hundreds of signatures from people and organizations expressing their opposition to AOL's use of Goodmail.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Esther Dyson defended the move in an editorial in *The New York Times*, saying "I hope Goodmail succeeds, and that it has lots of competition.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] I also think it and its competitors will eventually transform into services that more directly serve the interests of mail recipients.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Tim Lee of the Technology Liberation Front posted an article that questioned the Electronic Frontier Foundation's adopting a confrontational posture when dealing with private companies.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] SpamAssassin developer Justin Mason posted some criticism of the EFF's and Moveon's "going overboard" in their opposition to the scheme.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The dearaol.com campaign lost momentum and disappeared, with the last post to the now defunct dearaol.com blog—"AOL starts the shakedown" being made on May 9, 2006.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Comcast, who also used the service, announced on its website that Goodmail had ceased operations and as of February 4, 2011, they no longer used the service.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] On August 4, 2006, AOL released a compressed text file on one of its websites containing 20 million search keywords for over 650,000 users over a three-month period between March 1 and May 31, 2006, intended for research purposes.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL pulled the file from public access by August 7, but not before its wide distribution on the Internet by others.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Derivative research, titled *A Picture of Search*, was published by authors Pass, Chowdhury and Torgeson for The First International Conference on Scalable Information Systems.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The data were used by websites such as AOLstalker for entertainment purposes, where users of AOLstalker are encouraged to judge AOL clients based on the humorousness of personal details revealed by search behavior.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] In 2003, Jason Smathers, an AOL employee, was convicted of stealing America Online's 92 million screen names and selling them to a known spammer.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to conspiracy charges in 2005.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Smathers pled guilty to violations of the US CAN-SPAM Act of 2003.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] He was sentenced in August 2005 to 15 months in prison; the sentencing judge also recommended Smathers be forced to pay $84,000 in restitution, triple the $28,000 that he sold the addresses for.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] On February 27, 2012, a class action lawsuit was filed against Support.com, Inc. and partner AOL, Inc.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] The companies then offered to sell software—for which AOL allegedly charged $4.99 a month and Support.com $29—to remedy those problems.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Both AOL, Inc. and Support.com, Inc. settled on May 30, 2013, for $8.5 million.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] This included $25.00 to each valid class member and $100,000 each to Consumer Watchdog and the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL continues to market Computer Checkup.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Following media reports about PRISM, NSA's massive electronic surveillance program, in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including AOL.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] According to leaks of said program, AOL joined the PRISM program in 2011.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] At one time, most AOL users had an online "profile" hosted by the AOL Hometown service.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] When AOL Hometown was discontinued, users had to create a new profile on Bebo.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] This was an unsuccessful attempt to create a social network that would compete with Facebook.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] When the value of Bebo decreased to a tiny fraction of the $850 million AOL paid for it, users were forced to recreate their profiles yet again, on a new service called AOL Lifestream.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] AOL decided to shut down Lifestream on February 24, 2017, and gave users one month's notice to save photos and videos that had been uploaded to Lifestream.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] Following the shutdown, AOL no longer provides any option for hosting user profiles.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] During the Hometown/Bebo/Lifestream era, another user's profile could be displayed by clicking the "Buddy Info" button in the AOL Desktop software.
[src:bob-barker/aol-p02] After the shutdown of Lifestream, this was no longer supported, but opened to the AIM home page (www.aim.com), which also became defunct, redirecting to AOL's home page.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Born in Darrington, Washington, in modest circumstances, Barker spent most of his youth on the Rosebud Indian Reservation and was a citizen of the Rosebud Sioux Tribe.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker joined the United States Navy Reserve during World War II.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He worked part-time in radio while attending college.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 1950, Barker moved to California to pursue a broadcasting career.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He was given his own radio show, *The Bob Barker Show*, which ran for six years.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker began his game show career in 1956, hosting *Truth or Consequences*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker began hosting *The Price Is Right* in 1972.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He became an advocate for animal rights and of animal rights activism, supporting groups such as the United Activists for Animal Rights, People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, and the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 2007, Barker retired from hosting *The Price Is Right* after celebrating his 50-year career on television.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Regarded as a pop culture icon, Barker continued to make occasional appearances for several years into his retirement until 2015.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Robert William Barker was born on December 12, 1923, in Darrington, Washington, and spent most of his youth on the Rosebud Indian Reservation in Mission, South Dakota.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Indian Census Rolls, 1885–1940, list Barker as a citizen of the Rosebud Sioux Tribe, which the tribe publicly confirmed.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] His mother, Matilda ("Tillie") Valandra (née Matilda Kent Tarleton), was a schoolteacher; his father, Byron John Barker, was the foreman on the electrical high line through the state of Washington.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker's father was one-quarter Sicangu, and his mother non-Native, thus Barker was one-eighth Sicangu.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker once said, "I've always bragged about being part Indian, because they are a people to be proud of.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] And the Sioux were the greatest warriors of them all." He attended grade school on the Rosebud Reservation where his mother was a teacher.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker met his future wife, Dorothy Jo Gideon, at an Ella Fitzgerald concert while he was attending high school in Missouri; they began dating when he was 15.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker attended Drury College (now Drury University) in Springfield, Missouri, on a basketball athletic scholarship.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He was a member of the Epsilon Beta chapter of Sigma Nu fraternity at Drury.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker joined the United States Navy Reserve in 1943 during World War II to train as a fighter pilot but did not serve in combat.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On January 12, 1945, while on leave from the military, Barker married Dorothy Jo.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] After the war, he returned to Drury to finish his education, graduating *summa cum laude* with a degree in economics.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] While attending college in Drury, Barker worked his first media job at KTTS-FM Radio in Springfield.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He and his wife left Springfield and moved to Lake Worth Beach, Florida, and Barker was news editor and announcer at nearby WWPG 1340 AM in Palm Beach (now WPBR in Lantana).
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 1950, he moved to California to advance his broadcasting career.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker was given his own radio show, *The Bob Barker Show*, which ran for the next six years from Burbank.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker started hosting *Truth or Consequences* on December 31, 1956, and continued with the program until 1975.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In early 1972, Mark Goodson and Bill Todman began shopping a modernized revival of *The Price Is Right*, with Dennis James as host.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] NBC bought the syndicated nighttime version of the Show first with James at the helm.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Due to a contractual obligation and the fact that James was already viewed as the "NBC" Host, CBS wanted Bob Barker as the daytime host.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] After some initial resistance, Barker instead offered to host another upcoming CBS game show, Jack Barry's *The Joker's Wild* (which had difficulty finding a host and was scheduled to debut the same day as *Price*) to allow James to host *Price*, but CBS rejected this proposal.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In December 1974, James stepped in to host the daytime *The Price Is Right* for a week when Barker was ill.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] James was the only person to substitute on the daytime version of the show while Barker was hosting.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 1977, James' contract was not renewed, and Barker took over as host of the nighttime edition of *The Price Is Right* until its cancellation in 1980.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On September 4, 1972, Barker began hosting the CBS revival of *The Price Is Right*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On October 15, 1987, Barker did what other MCs almost never did then: he stopped using hair dye and let his hair go gray, its natural color by that time.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Following the death of Frank Wayne in 1988, Barker also assumed executive producer duties over *The Price Is Right*, in doing so gaining near-complete control over the program from then onward.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On October 31, 2006, Barker announced that he would retire from *The Price Is Right* in June 2007.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker taped his final episode on June 6, 2007, with the show airing twice on June 15; once in Daytime and once on Primetime.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On October 15, 2007, Drew Carey took over hosting duties on the show.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] After his retirement, Barker made three return appearances to *The Price is Right*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He first appeared on the episode that aired on April 16, 2009, to promote his new autobiography, *Priceless Memories*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker appeared in the Showcase round at the end of the show.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker made another guest appearance on the show to celebrate his 90th birthday, which aired on December 12, 2013.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker announced a contestant for the first time ever on the show, along with one showcase.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker's last appearance was a surprise appearance on April 1, 2015, for an April Fools' Day switch where he took Carey's place at the show's intro.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker hosted the first bid and pricing game of that day before handing the hosting duties back to Carey; Barker later appeared during the showcase.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In addition to the game shows for which he became famous, Barker also hosted the annual/biennial *Pillsbury Bake-Off* (the bake-off occurred every two years starting in 1976).
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 1978, he was the first host to have a male category champ.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] From 1969-1988 he also co-hosted CBS's coverage of the Rose Parade from Pasadena, California.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On September 7, 2009, Barker was a special guest host for *WWE Raw* (called "The Price is Raw") in Rosemont, Illinois.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Aired during a period when nearly every episode of the weekly wrestling show featured a celebrity guest host, with mixed results, Barker's appearance has been ranked the best of nearly 80 hosts.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker also agreed to be a rotating guest co-host on *The Huckabee Show*, a daily TV talk show hosted by Mike Huckabee.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker first appeared on the show on July 29, 2010.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker's fame from his television hosting roles also saw him become a popular guest on other shows, including as a semi-regular panelist on the game shows *Tattletales* (1975–1976, with wife Dorothy Jo) and *Match Game* (1973–1980).
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker sat in Richard Dawson's former place during the first week after Dawson permanently left *Match Game*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker often appeared in fiction as himself, usually in a cameo appearance, in shows including *The Nanny*, *The Bold and the Beautiful* *Futurama*, and *How I Met Your Mother*.In 1996, Barker played himself in the Adam Sandler comedy *Happy Gilmore*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In one scene, Barker beats up Gilmore after an altercation arising from their teaming up in a Pro-Am Golf Tournament.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] According to Sandler, the original choice for that scene was Ed McMahon, but Sandler said that McMahon was not fond of the script and they got Barker because of Chuck Norris training Barker in the martial arts.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker also played himself in the animated series *Family Guy,* starting in 2001 with the episode "Screwed the Pooch" with his last appearance being in 2008 in the episode "Tales of a Third Grade Nothing".
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 2007, during a CBS prime-time special commemorating Barker's career, the fight scene from *Happy Gilmore* was shown, after which Sandler made a surprise appearance on stage to read a poem paying tribute to Barker.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 2015, during Comedy Central's "Night of Too Many Stars" benefit show to battle autism, Barker and Sandler reunited for a video featuring the two of them in a follow-up fight at the hospital, which ends with both of them dying and going to heaven.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] However, Barker did play characters apart from himself in *Bonanza*, as a character named Mort in the 1960 episode "Denver McKee", and as a small business owner named Bob Barnacle in "Sanctuary!", an episode of the Nickelodeon animated series *SpongeBob SquarePants*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] About one year after his retirement from *The Price Is Right*, Barker appeared in a public service announcement promoting the transition to digital television in the United States.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] The advertisement was produced under the first proposed date of February 16, 2009, for the transition.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He later appeared in a commercial for State Farm Insurance's "Magic Jingle" campaign, where he made "a new car!" appear for a woman whose previous car was totaled by a giant concrete cylinder.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In another TV advertisement, Barker endorsed David Jolly, a candidate for the Republican Party nomination for the 2014 Florida's 13th congressional district special election.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Jolly won the nomination and ultimately won the seat.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker was honored after his death with an hour-long TV special celebrating his life.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker was married to Dorothy Jo Gideon from 1945 until her death from lung cancer at age 57 in 1981.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] From 1983 until his death, Barker was in a long-term relationship with Nancy Burnet, a self-described "radical" animal rights activist nearly 20 years younger than Barker.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] By mutual decision, Barker and Burnet were never married and lived in separate residences throughout their relationship.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker had no children with either woman, stating that he had seen friends who had poor relationships with their children and felt like he was too busy to properly raise a child; as of 2007, Barker stated that he had no regrets about his decision.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] During the early years of his relationship with Burnet, Barker also had a sexual relationship with Dian Parkinson, a model on *The Price Is Right*; other models on the program noted that the relationship was at one point close enough that there was a realistic chance of the two marrying.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker and Parkinson's relationship ended acrimoniously along with Parkinson's tenure on the program in 1993.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] From the late 2000s onward, Burnet described the relationship as a platonic friendship, even as Barker had become more interested in remarrying; she recalled a 2011 incident where Barker drafted a prenuptial agreement for Burnet's lawyer to review and revise as she felt fit, which she refused.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Burnet managed Barker's health and diet in retirement.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 1987, Barker requested the removal of fur prizes for the Miss USA pageant and stepped down as host when the producers refused.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] The suit was finally settled by the insurer in 1994.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker founded DJ&T Foundation in 1994, named after his late wife and mother, which has contributed millions of dollars to animal-neutering programs and funded animal rescue and park facilities all over the United States.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 2004, Barker donated $1 million (equivalent to $1.7 million in 2025) to Columbia Law School to support the study of animal rights.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 2009, Barker wrote a letter about three businesses in Cherokee, North Carolina, asking them to close their bear exhibits.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He threatened to not attend the 2009 Game Show Awards, where Barker was to receive a lifetime achievement award, because Betty White would be attending.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Although Barker had previously worked with White, he was feuding with her over the treatment of an elephant at the Los Angeles Zoo.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] White instead did not attend and pre-recorded her comments that she was scheduled to make about another awardee, Mark Goodson.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] That same year, Barker donated $1 million (equivalent to $1.4 million in 2021) to the University of Virginia Law School to support the study of animal rights.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He made similar donations to Harvard Law School, Stanford Law School, Georgetown University Law Center, Duke University School of Law, Northwestern University Pritzker School of Law, and University of California, Los Angeles.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 2010, the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society announced that it had purchased and outfitted a ship to interdict Japanese whaling operations in the Southern Ocean using $5 million (equivalent to $7.4 million in 2025) provided by Barker.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] The ship was then named the MY *Bob Barker*, and its existence was first revealed when it helped discover the location of the Japanese whaling fleet.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker participated in several PETA public service announcements over the years, including one that claimed that vegan diets prevent Alzheimer's disease.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 2010, he donated $2.5 million (equivalent to $3.7 million in 2025) toward the purchase of office space for the organization in Los Angeles.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In the late 1980s, Barker accused the American Humane Society and the United Activists for Animal Rights of condoning animal cruelty on the set of *Project X* and in several other media projects on the basis of allowing a cattle prod and a gun on set, and a rumored beating of a chimpanzee on set.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] American Humane responded by suing Barker for $10 million, citing libel, slander and invasion of privacy.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] American Humane claimed that there had been a two-year "vendetta" against them behind the accusations.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In a series of public advertisements along with the lawsuit, American Humane responded to Barker's claims that his allegations were made based on insufficient and misleading information.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] The suit was eventually settled by Barker's insurance company, which paid American Humane $300,000.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In 1994, former model Dian Parkinson filed a lawsuit against Barker alleging sexual harassment following a three-year affair while working on *The Price Is Right*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Parkinson, who alleged that she was extorted by threats of firing, later dropped her lawsuit, claiming the stress from the ordeal was damaging her health.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker countersued for slander, but Hallstrom prevailed, receiving a settlement in 2005.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Though she was not required to sign a non-disclosure agreement, she limited her comments about Barker until after his death, fearing retribution from him.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Curling claimed that she was demoted to an "intolerable work environment" backstage, which caused her to leave the job.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Curling, who is black, also alleged that the show's producers, including Barker, created a hostile work environment in which black employees and contestants were discriminated against.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] A few months later, Barker was removed from the lawsuit, and in September 2009, the lawsuit was dismissed.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Curling's attorney stated that he planned to appeal the dismissal of the lawsuit.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In January 2012, the California Court of Appeals affirmed the dismissal.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On September 16, 1999, Barker was in Washington, D.C., to testify before Congress regarding proposed legislation that would ban captive elephants from traveling shows, such as circuses.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] While preparing for the presentation, Barker experienced what he called clumsiness in his right hand.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker was admitted to George Washington University Hospital and diagnosed with a partially blocked left carotid artery.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] He underwent carotid endarterectomy to remove the blockage.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] The procedure went well enough that Barker was able to return to work within the month.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Three years later, Barker had two additional health crises after taping the 30th-season finale of *The Price is Right*.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] While lying in the sun on May 30, 2002, he experienced a stroke and was hospitalized; six weeks later, on July 11, Barker underwent prostate surgery.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Both hospitalizations occurred at George Washington University Hospital in Washington, D.C. and both surgeries were successful.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker had several mild bouts with skin cancer, a result of his frequent tanning.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker consulted a dermatologist regularly to make sure any cancers were caught and removed before they spread; they did not pose a threat to his life.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On October 20, 2015, two police officers passing Barker's Los Angeles-area home saw him trip and fall on a sidewalk.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] They called an ambulance which took him to Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, where Barker received stitches for an injured forehead and was released; he also hurt his left knee.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker slipped and hit his head at home on June 19, 2017.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] His maid drove him to the emergency room, where Barker was checked and released.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] His representative said it was not as serious as his earlier fall.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] In October and November 2018, Barker was rushed to the hospital for severe back pain.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker suffered another fall in January 2019, but he was not hospitalized.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker's last public interview was with *People* in August 2021, in which he discussed *The Price Is Right's* upcoming 50th season on air.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] As of 2022, Burnet stated that, other than some non-prescription supplements such as collagen and a meal replacement drink to replenish nutrients not found naturally in Barker's vegetarian diet, he took only one prescription medication for hypothyroidism.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] On August 26, 2023, Barker died at his home in Los Angeles at the age of 99 of natural causes related to following several years fighting with Alzheimer's disease, a condition that Burnet and Barker's publicity team had kept hidden from the public.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Hypertension, hyperlipidemia and hypothyroidism were listed as secondary causes of death.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker was interred alongside his wife at Forest Lawn Memorial Park – Hollywood Hills.
[src:bob-barker/bob-barker] Barker's autobiography, *Priceless Memories*, written with former *Los Angeles Times* book review editor Digby Diehl, was published on April 6, 2009.
